Anomalous spring observations

Published

March 6, 2025

We identified observations of plant phenophases in Natureâ€™s Notebook (NN) that were earlier than normal in 2025. We compared 2025 observations with observations collected in 2009-2024 for plants within 100 km and within 1000 m elevation of the plant observed in 2025. We limited analyses to phenophases in 4 phenophase classes: initial vegetative growth (class 1), leaves or needles (3), flowers or cones (6), and open flowers or cones (7), and only evaluated whether an observation was early if there were at least 20 observations for that species and phenophase over 8 or more years between 2009 and 2024.

We classified a 2025 observation as early if it was earlier than 95% of first-of-year observations in 2009-2024, and as an outlier if it was a Tukey outlier (2025 observation earlier than Q1 - 1.5 * IQR). We also noted if the observation was as early or earlier than the earliest date ever recorded in NN for that species, phenophase, and region (earliest).

In the tables below, we list all of the 2025 observations that were considered early or an outlier by phenophase class. Histograms displaying distribution of observations in prior years that were used to assess 2025 potential anomalies are at the bottom of the document.
